<h2>I. A Quiet Infiltration Underway</h2>

<p>In the fall of 2025, OpenAI announced a partnership with <strong>400,000 U.S. teachers</strong> to shape the future of AI in schools. The same week, a high school student wrote in <em>The Atlantic</em> that "AI Is Demolishing My Education." Professors told <em>The Guardian</em> they "wish they could push ChatGPT off a cliff." Meanwhile, <em>Scientific American</em> ran the story of a mother who used vibe coding to build an AI tutor for her dyslexic son — with results that surpassed every human tutor she had hired.</p>

<p>This is what AI integration into America's education system actually looks like in 2026: <strong>not one unified narrative, but infiltration at different speeds, forms, and intentions across every corner of the ecosystem.</strong></p>

<p>The data backs this up. Brookings' latest research on generative AI in tutoring (May 2026) found significant positive effects — but only when teachers were involved in designing and implementing the AI tools. On the other side, student AI adoption rates now exceed 90% (DemandSage, 2026), while the majority of schools still lack a formal AI use policy.</p>

<p><strong>The defining characteristic of this infiltration: users at the bottom (students) have fully embraced AI, while institutions at the top (schools, teachers, policymakers) are still debating whether AI is good or bad.</strong></p>

<h2>II. Three Paths Into the Classroom</h2>

<h3>Path One: Platform Down — Khan Academy's Khanmigo</h3>

<p>Khan Academy's AI tutor Khanmigo, honed over two years, is now being piloted in multiple U.S. school districts. Its design principle: "guide, don't give answers." When a student asks a math problem, Khanmigo walks through questions rather than providing the answer directly. <em>60 Minutes</em> dedicated a feature to it.</p>

<p>But a deep-dive by <em>Chalkbeat</em> (May 2026) exposed the limitations: AI tutors remain helpless when faced with real classroom behavior issues — zoning out, acting out, emotional breakdowns. <strong>AI excels at "knowledge transfer," but a classroom has never been just about knowledge transfer.</strong></p>

<h3>Path Two: Resistance and Retreat — South Korea's Cautionary Tale</h3>

<p>The most instructive global reference point is South Korea. In 2025, the Korean government launched an ambitious AI digital textbook initiative — and met with fierce resistance from teachers' unions. Korea's Board of Audit and Inspection ultimately ruled the plan "riddled with serious procedural flaws," and by late 2025 the government had withdrawn its AI textbook rollout.</p>

<p><em>Business Insider</em> commented: <strong>"South Korea's teacher revolt is a warning for the U.S."</strong> Korea's case demonstrates that when AI is top-down "force-fed" into an education system, no matter how good the technology, it meets institutional resistance.</p>

<h3>Path Three: Parental Self-Help — Grassroots AI Education Experiments</h3>

<p>The most unexpected path comes from parents. <em>Scientific American</em> profiled Arlyn Gajilan: a news industry professional, not a technologist, whose son Tobey repeatedly broke down over his dyslexia. Using GPTs, she built a custom AI tutor. She told the AI: "You are a special education teacher with expertise in dyslexia," then fed it Tobey's assessments, evaluations, and favorite interests (dragons from Wings of Fire, Nerf battles). The result? Tobey, for the first time, voluntarily wrote a story — a complex narrative about dragon warfare, with sophisticated sentence structures.</p>

<p><strong>This path reveals something profound: when the formal system fails, AI gives individuals the ability to bypass the system entirely.</strong></p>

<h2>III. The Core Insight: Education Is Being "LangChain-ified"</h2>

<p>Putting these three paths together reveals a structural shift:</p>

<p>Traditional education is a <strong>monolithic black box</strong> — curriculum design, teaching, grading, tutoring, testing, college counseling — all performed by one institution. AI is taking this black box and <strong>splitting it into microservices</strong>:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Knowledge delivery → LLM + RAG systems</li>
  <li>Grading → AI scoring engines</li>
  <li>Individual tutoring → AI tutor bots</li>
  <li>Curriculum design → AI course generators</li>
  <li>College counseling → AI advisory systems</li>
</ul>

<p>These "microservices" were previously inseparable because only human teachers could perform all functions simultaneously. AI allows each to function independently. <strong>The education value chain is being decoupled.</strong></p>

<p>Khanmigo de-coupled "tutoring." OpenAI's 400K teacher partnerships de-coupled "lesson planning." Scientific American's mother didn't need any institution — she assembled her own education system.</p>

<p><strong>This is reminiscent of what decentralized finance did to banking a decade ago: not replacing the bank, but pulling the bank's functions apart one by one on top of a peer-to-peer architecture. Education is undergoing the same process.</strong></p>

<h2>IV. The Real Challenge Isn't Technology — It's Redefining the Human Role</h2>

<p>The anxiety of South Korean teachers and American educators shares the same root: <strong>AI has entered teachers' territory, but the boundary of their role has not been redefined.</strong></p>

<p>I asked a friend who teaches at an American public middle school: "Do you think your job will change with AI?" He said: "Less time grading and creating lesson plans, but the same amount of time dealing with student emotional issues and parent communication."</p>

<p>This answer hits the core: <strong>What AI can replace is "information-processing" teaching labor. What it cannot replace is "social-emotional" labor.</strong></p>

<p>Geoffrey Hinton has repeatedly stated: AI has no consciousness, no intent, no real understanding. The most valuable part of education — motivating an unwilling child, calming an anxious parent, discovering a student's unique gift — requires exactly the kind of human intuition and empathy that AI lacks.</p>

<p><strong>The real question isn't "Will AI replace teachers?" It's "When AI takes over 60% of repetitive tasks, are the remaining 40% worth doing — and can we do them well?"</strong></p>

<h2>V. What This Means for China</h2>

<p>Bringing the lens back to China's perspective:</p>

<p><strong>First</strong>, America's AI education shift is moving from "top-down design" to "grassroots infiltration." OpenAI's teacher partnership is influencing curriculum design. Khanmigo's district coverage is expanding. Even parents without technical backgrounds can bypass the system.</p>

<p><strong>Second</strong>, "forced top-down" approaches face institutional resistance. Korea's lesson is clear: large-scale AI education policy without deep teacher consultation is doomed.</p>

<p><strong>Third</strong>, for Chinese edtech companies looking to go global: the competitive moat isn't AI capability alone — it's whether your product can embed itself into America's "social-emotional school network." The AI tutoring function itself is no longer a differentiator (ChatGPT already has it). What gets into schools is a product that helps teachers solve problems, not one that replaces them.</p>

<p><strong>As AI begins to penetrate the most conservative and institutionalized system in society, we may be witnessing not just a technological upgrade of education, but a restructuring of education's production relations. The speed, direction, and cost of this restructuring will determine how the next generation learns and grows in the AI era.</strong></p>

<hr class="article-divider">

<p><em>📍 humanaifit insight: Education may be the most important application of Human-AI Fit — not because AI can teach better, but because human teachers can finally return to their true calling of "nurturing" while leaving "instruction" to the machine. What this requires is not technological capability, but the courage to redefine the role of educator.</em></p>

